{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Of all the great philosophers, Hegel is one of the most difficult to understand, and, at least by some philosophers, one of the most despised.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Russell and Schopenhauer thought that his philosophy was devoid of any useful meaning, and Popper blamed him for the rise of totalitarianism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "What is his position today? Is he still worth reading? Are his contributions to thought useful on the twenty first century? Or is he, as many maintain, out of date, and wrong anyway?",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Hegel's was interested not so much in understanding a given state of affairs, as in understanding a process of change.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Depending on what context you are considering, it's goal is Absolute Knowledge, Absolute Freedom, or an Organic Society.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Hegel thought that in order to make anything of sense data that is useful for further thinking or action, we have to suppose other concepts for it's interpretation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Hegel calls this interpretation process \"mediation\", and insisted that without these supporting, mediating concepts, sense data are blind.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Consciousness therefore must have a content which allows the interpretation of sense data.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Eventually, by way of this communal effort, we arrive at what in Hegel's view is \"perception\".",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "New criteria emerge as the process goes forward and \"understanding\" emerges.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "With work and study, this in turn becomes \"scientific cognition\", all of which has developed from the original sense data.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "He considers the intersubjective conditions necessary for consciousness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "He believes that consciousness of an external object needs an awareness of oneself as a distinct subject, or self consciousness.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Furthermore, we recognise others' self-consciousness.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "We think in terms of a network or pattern of mutual recognition between subjects or agents i.e ourselves and other people.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "We share a common system of perceptions and understandings, and this forms a total complex system, or spirit.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Hegel believes he has moved from the subjective mind of the agent to the objective spirit of the system of agents.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "He thereby invokes distinct patterns of social interaction and of reciprocal recognition.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Hegel's version is more metaphysical.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "He refers to something which is part of yourself, of your Geist, yet foreign, alien or hostile.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "This something makes us confront ourselves, question what we are doing.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Eventually we reach a solution.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "A process of self-division, self-alienation and finally overcoming ensues.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "At the very least, we reach a way of living with ourselves and in society.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "According to Hegel, our Geist becomes part of the larger Geist or spirit, and we move towards absolute knowledge, freedom and reality.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Having dealt with alienation, we are now in a position to see what Hegel meant by the dialectic, which, as you infer, he saw as the process by which mankind would move forward to achieve the goal of being at one with the world and society.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "A process of self-division, self-alienation and finally overcoming ensues, you remember.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU28": {
      "text": "When we feel alienation, we confront it, solve the problem and move on.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU29": {
      "text": "Then the process repeats.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU30": {
      "text": "The common description of the dialectic in both Hegel and Marx is one of an iterative process of thesis, anti-thesis and resolution.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU31": {
      "text": "Hegel came directly after Kant in German philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU32": {
      "text": "Kant's transcendental idealism was uppermost in Hegel's mind when he started out.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU33": {
      "text": "Hegel disagreed.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU34": {
      "text": "He saw the noumenal world as work in progress.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU35": {
      "text": "We would get there eventually.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU36": {
      "text": "But it would take time.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU37": {
      "text": "In short, via the dialectic.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU38": {
      "text": "Humans want to make working assumptions, because they want solutions to avoid alienation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU39": {
      "text": "They don't always get their assumptions right, so along comes another thinker, or even another generation of people, who disbelieve, or negate, the first assumption, but eventually in so doing resolve the problem.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU40": {
      "text": "While this sounds like the triadic thesis-antithesis-resolution sequence, some of Hegel's triads are more vaguely defined and general.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU41": {
      "text": "The difference with Hegel is that he takes this general task of philosophy and elevates it to a position where it is a long term process covering the whole of history.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU42": {
      "text": "His most famous and immediate follower was Marx.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU43": {
      "text": "He was not so much interested in the dissolving of the Kantian noumenon, or in reconciling currently opposing arguments.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU44": {
      "text": "His interests were essentially in society, and the material business of the world of work and man's place in the practical world of the everyday.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU45": {
      "text": "Marx saw the feudal system turning to the much more successful capitalist system, which he thought would eventually turn into something else, which he called communism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU46": {
      "text": "He was a student of Hegel, took Hegel's historical view of the dialectic, but related it to material society, not to general philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU47": {
      "text": "Hence the Marxist term dialectic materialism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU48": {
      "text": "In his first book, The Phenomenology of Spirit, it is presented as historical development in society.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU49": {
      "text": "A dogmatic thought is gradually replaced by a system in which claims are open to to correction, because the dogmatic thought cannot be justified and therefore stand up to scrutiny.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU50": {
      "text": "Why does reason prevail? Because we naturally seek society, and become acculturated.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
